            "creation_date": 1498231717,
            "body": "<p>Include the JAR in the classpath.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 44725084,
            "question_id": 44725052
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/qHssd.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 11166277,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 8194873,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/8194873/joao",
                "reputation": 86,
                "display_name": "Joao"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1498288233,
            "creation_date": 1498232047,
            "body": "<p>Include the jar on the classpath:<\/p>\n\n<p>java -classpath [PATH_TO_JAR] YOUR_CLASS<\/p>\n\n<p>And on your classes import the classes you wish to use:<\/p>\n\n<p>import package.CLASS_2_USE_1\nImport package.CLASS_2_USE_2<\/p>\n\n<p>This assuming the classes are public.<\/p>\n\n<p>Edit: If you want to load classes form jars supplied at runtime it's probably a good idea to agree on a fixed set of methods and class names. You can see how to do it on this thread:<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/60764/how-should-i-load-jars-dynamically-at-runtime\">How should I load Jars dynamically at runtime?<\/a><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 44725204,
